In 2006, Meryl Streep became an eternal face for our generation after embodying one of the internet's favorite girlbosses. In *The Devil Wears Prada*, she is Miranda Priestly, and she is an icon. She is powerful, respected, and feared. She commands rooms full of men. She runs a global fashion empire. She is, in every way, what many would call a feminist success story.

And that is inspiring and empowering to other women… or is it not?

In case you were planning on skipping the first movie before watching the second, here's a recap.

The story follows Andy, a girl who has just finished journalism school and is looking for her first job. By chance, she is recommended by an employment agency for a position at the fashion magazine *Runway*. And there, she meets Miranda, the editor-in-chief of the magazine.

Miranda is the typical abusive boss who rips off her coat and throws it in her employees’ faces, makes them do the housework for her daughters, and criticizes Andy's clothes with contempt. But then, in one of the many times Andy cries, she turns to a co-worker who tells her:

> “If you're unhappy, then quit. Thousands of girls would kill themselves for this job. You're hoping to get a reward from Miranda for simply doing your job.”

If you keep up with debates about feminism on and off the internet, you probably heard that the way to combat sexism is by placing women in advantageous positions — whether in company management, institutional politics, or positive representations in films, cartoons, and dolls.

We refer to this approach as **liberal feminism** because, although it acknowledges the historically disadvantaged position women have occupied, it believes the solution lies in individual empowerment, with some women taking on the roles traditionally held by men.

In other words: more Mirandas.

---

Another common term in online debates is *sisterhood*. But what even is that?

The dictionary describes it as:

> “Union of women who share the same ideals and purposes, normally of feminist content, characterized by the mutual support shown between these women.”

There are many problems with that idea when used through a liberal feminist approach.

For starters, women do not share the same purposes and ideals — and yes, I'm talking about class interests.

Margaret Thatcher, for example, the first woman to become Prime Minister of England, implemented a regime that doubled the number of poor people in England. Moreover, she was responsible for massacring Argentinians in the Falklands War; she supported Apartheid in South Africa and backed dictatorships in Latin America and on the African continent.

The interests of Latin American and African women who fought for democracy in their countries did not align with Thatcher's. Likewise, the class interests of precarious women in England whose labor rights were ruined by Thatcher's liberal policies also did not align with hers.

Hillary Clinton, during her time as U.S. Secretary of State, was one of the main coordinators of the war against Libya. If I turned to a Libyan woman who had her country devastated and lost her husband and son in the war, and told her she should go easy on Hillary out of “sisterhood,” she would probably tell me to go f*** myself — and she wouldn't be wrong.

